Problem Statement

Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the kth largest element in the array.

⚠️ Note: This is the kth largest, not distinct.

Example 1
Input: nums = [3,2,1,5,6,4], k = 2
Output: 5

Example 2
Input: nums = [3,2,3,1,2,4,5,5,6], k = 4
Output: 4

Best Interview Approach: Min Heap (Priority Queue)
Idea

Maintain a min heap of size k

The heap keeps the k largest elements seen so far

The root of the heap is the kth largest element

Algorithm

Create a min heap.

Traverse the array:

Add current element to the heap

If heap size exceeds k, remove smallest element

Return the root of the heap.

Time & Space Complexity

Time Complexity: O(N log k)

Space Complexity: O(k)

Java Code
import java.util.*;

public class KthLargestElement {

    public static int findKthLargest(int[] nums, int k) {
        PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            minHeap.offer(num);

            if (minHeap.size() > k) {
                minHeap.poll();
            }
        }

        return minHeap.peek();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {3,2,1,5,6,4};
        int k = 2;
        System.out.println("Kth Largest Element: " + findKthLargest(nums, k));
    }
}

Line-by-Line Code Explanation
PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();


Creates a min heap.

minHeap.offer(num);


Adds element to heap.

if (minHeap.size() > k)


Ensures heap stores only k elements.

minHeap.poll();


Removes the smallest element so only largest remain.

return minHeap.peek();


Root contains the kth largest element.

Example Walkthrough
nums = [3,2,1,5,6,4], k = 2

Heap process:
Add 3 → [3]
Add 2 → [2,3]
Add 1 → [1,3,2] → remove 1
Add 5 → [3,5] → remove 3
Add 6 → [5,6]
Add 4 → [4,6,5] → remove 4

Answer = 5

Why Interviewers Love This Problem

✔ Heap knowledge
✔ Optimized thinking
✔ Avoids sorting (O(N log N))
✔ Clean explanation
